l regimes created dissimilar social spaces even on the same streets and in the same buildings. His narrative leads us to rethink how the late imperial Habsburg and Romanov, Stalinist and post-Stalinist Soviet, interwar Polish, and Nazi German regimes produced, structured, and controlled urban space. Focusing on railway workers, the book also draws attention to the history of Lviv’s wage earners, who constituted the majority of the city’s adult population.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aRailroad stationszUkrainezLʹvivxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aBrezhnev.  aFranz Joseph I.  aLviv.  aPolish and Nazi regimes.  aStalinist and post-Stalinist.  ahistory of railway workers.  ainterwar.  alate imperial Habsburg and Romanov.  arailway terminal.  atwentieth-century history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753172040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487531720423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487531720.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles